We are now up to proving {\hyperref[{ThirdRes}]{Theorem \ref*{{ThirdRes}}}}.

\begin{corollary} \label{AbstFratCor}

Let $G$ be a group for which every subgroup $H$ whose profinite completion is finitely generated, is itself finitely generated. Let $n \in \mathbb{N}$, and let $\mathcal{F} \neq \emptyset$ be a family of $n$-generated subgroups of $G$. Then $\mathcal{F}$ contains a maximal element.

\end{corollary}

\begin{proof}

Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a chain in $\mathcal{F}$, and let $U$ be its union. Since $\mathcal{C}$ is a chain, {\hyperref[{ProfRankBoundCor}]{Corollary \ref*{{ProfRankBoundCor}}}} implies that $d(\widehat{U}) \leq n$. By our assumption on $G$, there exists a finite generating set $S \subseteq U$. Since $\mathcal{C}$ is a chain, we can find an $R \in \mathcal{C}$ which contains $S$, and thus all of $U$. Therefore, $U = R \in \mathcal{F}$ is an upper bound for $\mathcal{C}$. By Zorn's Lemma, $\mathcal{F}$ has a maximal element.

\end{proof}

